America’s Health Rankings: The mission of America’s Health Rankings (AHR) is to provide a wide variety of health and health-related information to help policymakers, advocates and individuals understand a population’s health in a holistic, inclusive manner.

  • Where you can see this data: It exists here.
  • How we used their data: We used the latest version of each of the following three datasets in our narrative to compare Texas health outcomes to health outcomes in other states to understand where Texas fell in the bottom half of state rankings across the various measures that America’s Health Rankings Reports on throughh their Annual Report, Health of Women and Children, and their Senior Report.
    • The AHR 2018 Annual Report is the longest running annual assessment of the nation’s health on a state-by-state basis. For nearly three decades, America’s Health Rankings® Annual Report has analyzed a comprehensive set of behaviors, public and health policies, community and environmental conditions, and clinical care data to provide a holistic view of the health of the people in the nation.
      • The following measures came from AHR’s Annual Report: “Adverse Childhood Experiences”, "Cardiovascular Deaths", “Diabetes”, “Infectious Disease”, “Low Birthweight”, “Mental Health Providers”, “Obesity”, “Preventable Hospitalizations”, “Primary Care Physicians”, “Stroke” and “Uninsured”.
    • The AHR 2018 Health of Women and Children Report is the newest state rankings report. With a focus on women of reproductive age, infants and children under age 18, this report emphasizes the population groups where change can make generational differences.
      • The following measures came from AHR’s Health of Women and Children Report: “Immunizations - Children”, “Maternal Mortality”, and “Supportive Neighborhoods”.
      • IMPORTANT NOTE: These datasets were pulled in during the first week of September. In the weeks since September 5th, the AHR 2019 Health of Women and Children Report was released. As we did not have sufficient time to include this recently released data, the 2019 AHR Health of Women and Children report will be integrated into these rankings as soon as possible:
    • The AHR 2019 Senior Report recently completed its fifth year of presenting a comparative health report for the U.S. population aged 65 and older.
      • The following measures came from AHR’s Senior Report: "Frequent Mental Distress - Seniors".

Bureau of Economic Analysis: The Bureau of Economic Analysis (BEA) promotes a better understanding of the U.S. economy by providing the most timely, relevant, and accurate economic accounts data in an objective and cost-effective manner.

  • Where you can see this data: It exists here and here
  • How we used their data: We used their GDP by State estimates to generate the historical GDP Charts for Texas. To generate the share of Total GDP by Urban and Rural Counties, we had to merge two datasets. The first was BEA’s Prototype GDP by County released in December 2018 that provides County=Level estimates of GDP for 2012-2015 and the second was the U.S. Census Bureau’s [County Rurality Level: 2010] dataset, which provides breakdowns of every US County’s rurality based on the counts from the most recent Decennial Census in 2010. We then followed the Census Bureau’s methodology of classifying counties as urban or rural with one exception. The Census has two rural types (mostly or all) and one type of urban (mostly). For the purposes of this interactive–which is aimed at a general audience—we classified counties using a modified version of their methodology, where a county is either mostly urban or mostly rural based on the greater share of a given population type within each county. After joining that classification for each county to the GDP by County datasets, we aggregated the values of “Mostly Urban GDP” and “Mostly Rural GDP” for each year and divided those values by the total GDP for each of those years. What we found is that between 2012-2015, the distribution of GDP among Rural and Urban counties hardly varies. In Urban areas, it varied from 94.3% to 94.4% of GDP and 5.6% to 5.7% of GDP in Rural areas. We took the latest estimate from 2015, which was the 94.4% and 5.6% breakdown for the purposes of this slide..
library(tidyverse)      # Load the `tidyverse` package
library(janitor)        # Load the `janitor` package
library(readxl)         # Load the `readxl` package

# CODE TO ANALYZE CENSUS BUREAU DATA & CLASSIFY COUNTIES AS MOSTLY URBAN OR MOSTLY RURAL
county_import <- read_excel("Slide 9/County_Rural_Lookup.xlsx", skip=3) %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  filter(state=="TX") %>% 
  rename(county_fips=1,county_name=3, tot_pop=5, `Mostly Urban`=6,`Mostly Rural`=7) %>% 
  select(-2,-4,-8) %>% 
  gather(pop_type, value, 4:5) %>% 
  mutate(share=round(value/tot_pop, digits=3),
         pct=share) %>%
  mutate_at(vars(pct), scales::percent) %>% 
  group_by(county_name) %>% 
  slice(which.max(share)) %>% 
  ungroup() %>% 
  mutate(county_name=gsub(pattern=", Texas", replacement="", x=county_name),
         county_fips=gsub(pattern="^48", replacement = "", x=county_fips)) 

# IMPORT THE GDP BY COUNTY DATA FROM THE BUREAU OF ECONOMIC ANALYSIS

county_gdp <- read_excel("Slide 4/data/GCP_Release_1.xlsx") %>% 
  clean_names %>% 
  filter(postal=="TX",
         line_code=="1") %>% 
  rename(gdp_2012=6,
         gdp_2013=7,
         gdp_2014=8,
         gdp_2015=9) %>% 
  separate(fips, into=c("state", "county_fips"), sep=2)

# JOIN THE GDP BY COUNTY DATA FROM THE BUREAU OF ECONOMIC ANALYSIS
# WITH THE URBAN/RURAL COUNTY CLASSIFICATIONS DERIVED FROM THE CENSUS 

county_gdp_ur <- county_import %>% 
  left_join(ur_classify, by="county_fips") %>% 
  gather(year, gdp, 7:10) %>% 
  mutate(year=gsub(pattern="gdp_", replacement="",x=year),
         gdp=as.numeric(gdp))

# GROUP BY EACH YEAR AND POPULATION TYPE (URBAN/RURAL), 
# THEN SUMMARIZE GDP VALUES FOR EACH YEAR BY THAT POPULATION TYPE.

avg_urb_rur_gdp <- county_gdp_ur %>% 
  group_by(year, pop_type) %>% 
  summarise(tot_gdp = sum(gdp)) %>% 
  ungroup()

# DIVIDE THE TOTAL OF EACH YEAR'S URBAN GDP AND RURAL GDP
# FROM THE TOTAL GDP VALUES REPORTED BY BEA THAT YEAR IN
# ORDER TO DERIVE URBAN + RURAL SHARES OF TOTAL GDP IN TEXAS.

tot_urb_rur_gdp <- avg_urb_rur_gdp %>% 
  spread(pop_type, tot_gdp) %>% 
  mutate(tot_gdp=(`Mostly Urban`+`Mostly Rural`)) %>% 
  gather(pop_type, group_gdp, 2:3) %>% 
  select(1,3,4,2) %>% 
  mutate(gdp_share=round(group_gdp/tot_gdp, digits=3))

County Health Rankings: The County Health Rankings & Roadmaps program is a collaboration between the Robert Wood Johnson Foundation and the University of Wisconsin Population Health Institute. The annual County Health Rankings measure vital health factors, including high school graduation rates, obesity, smoking, unemployment, access to healthy foods, the quality of air and water, income inequality, and teen births in nearly every county in America. The annual Rankings provide a revealing snapshot of how health is influenced by where we live, learn, work and play.

  • Where you can see this data: It exists in the data explorer, under “Health”.
  • How we used their data: We used their county health rankings to provide data in the health explorer for each county on a handful of relevant statistics.

Federal Communications Commission: The Federal Communications Commission regulates interstate and international communications by radio, television, wire, satellite, and cable in all 50 states, the District of Columbia and U.S. territories. An independent U.S. government agency overseen by Congress, the Commission is the federal agency responsible for implementing and enforcing America’s communications law and regulations.

  • Where you can see this data: It exists here.
  • How we used their data: We used their estimate of a 31% gap in Rural broadband access (found here on page 48), along with an analysis of their Form 477 Broadband Deployment Data - December 2017 (version 2) to create the map of Broadband Access in Texas.
  • How we analyzed their Broadband Deployment Data: The FCC data for Texas came in a large CSV file, which we read into RStudio using the tidyverse. Then, we converted all column headers to be machine readable using the janitor package, which speeds up analysis. In the raw format of the data provided by FCC, census blocks (all of which were tagged by county) were not initially classified as meeting the standard or not meeting the FCC’s standard. They only had records of advertised speeds in each census block within each county. Our task was to take those speeds and determine whether or not a each census block in each of the 254 counties met the FCC’s standard of 25mbps download speed and 3mbps upload speed. So we wrote the script below to reclassify each census block, and assigned value of 1 to each census block so we could get accurate counts of how many census blocks met the standard in a given county and how many did not meet the standard. Once we aggregated counts for the number of blocks meeting or not meeting the FCC Standard in each county, we took both of those figures and divided them by the total number of census blocks in each county. At this point, we were able to then map out the share of census blocks in each county with Broadband Access that met the FCC’s standard of 25mbps download speed and 3mbps upload speed.
library(tidyverse) # Load the `tidyverse` package
library(janitor)   # Load the `janitor` package

# STEP 1: Read in the RAW FCC Data and Make Column Headers Machine Readable (Clean)

fcc_TXterrestrial_raw <- read_csv("raw_data/TX-Fixed-Dec2017-v2.csv") %>%   # Read the Data
  clean_names()                                                             # Clean Column Headers

# STEP 2: Reclassify FCC's Advertised Data Speeds For Each Census Tract In A County
#         And Determine Whether or Not It Meets FCC's 25/3 Standard. 

fcc_TXterrestrial_county <- fcc_TXterrestrial_raw %>%         # Start with the Raw Data
  mutate(blockcode=as.character(block_code),                  # Duplicate the Block Code Column To Extract FIPS Codes
         block_code=as.character(block_code)) %>%      
  separate(blockcode, into=c("state_id","other1"), sep=2) %>% # Extract States
  separate(other1, into=c("county_id","other2"), sep=3) %>%   # Extract Counties
  separate(other2, into=c("tract_id","block_id"), sep=6) %>%  # Extract Counties
  select(-block_id) %>%                                       # Drop Duplicated Block Column
  mutate(is_25_3=case_when(                                   # Create A New Column That Classifies A Census Blocks (1/2)
    max_ad_down >= 25 & max_ad_up >= 3 ~ "Yes",               # As Meeting FCC's Standard or Not, Based on Advertised Speeds (2/2)
    TRUE ~ "No"
  )) %>% 
  mutate(count=as.numeric(1)) %>%                             # Assign Each Census Block A Numeric Value of 1     
  group_by(county_id, is_25_3) %>%                            # Group By The County ID and New Classification
  summarise(sum=sum(count)) %>%                               # Summarize All Values of 1 Assigned To Census Blocks
  spread(is_25_3,sum) %>%                                     # Create A Column for Each Summary County Type of "Yes" + "No" 
  mutate(tot=Yes+No) %>%                                      # Sum Up The Values of All Census Blocks
  mutate(with=round(Yes/tot, digits=3),                       # Create Estimates of Counties with Broadband Access
         without=round(No/tot, digits=3))                     # Create Estimates of Counties without Broadband Access

library(tidyverse)

## LOAD THE TEXAS DEMOGRAPHIC CENTER PROJECTIONS DATA

pop_proj_data <- read_csv("Slide 5/2018allcntyindage.csv") %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  filter(str_detect(year,"2019|2036")) %>% 
  rename(county_fips=fips)

## CALCULATE THE INCREASE IN POPULATION 65+
## BETWEEN 2019 AND 2036

pop_65 <- pop_proj_data %>% 
  filter(county_fips=="000",
         age_in_yrs_num>=65) %>% 
  group_by(year) %>% 
  summarise(tot_pop_65plus=sum(total))

## CALCULATE THE INCREASE IN NON-WHITE POPULATION
## BETWEEN 2019 AND 2036

pop_non_white <- pop_proj_data %>% 
  filter(county_fips=="000",
         age_in_yrs_num==-1) %>% 
  select(year, nh_white_total,nh_black_total,hispanic_total,nh_asian_total,nh_other_total) %>% 
  gather(race_group, total, 2:6) %>% 
  mutate(group=case_when(
    race_group=="nh_white_total" ~ "White",
    TRUE ~ "Non-White"
  )) %>% 
  group_by(year, group) %>% 
  summarise(tot_pop_NW=sum(total))

## CALCULATE THE INCREASE IN POPULATION OF CURRENT URBAN AREAS
## BETWEEN 2019 AND 2036

pop_urb_rur <- pop_proj_data %>% 
  left_join(ur_classify, by="county_fips") %>% 
  filter(county_fips!="000",
         age_in_yrs_num==-1) %>% 
  group_by(year, pop_type) %>% 
  summarise(tot_pop_UR=sum(total)) %>% 
  spread(pop_type,tot_pop_UR) %>% 
  clean_names() %>% 
  mutate(tot_pop=mostly_urban+mostly_rural) %>% 
  mutate(urb_share=mostly_urban/tot_pop,
         rur_share=mostly_rural/tot_pop) %>% 
  mutate_at(vars(urb_share, rur_share), scales::percent)

## CALCULATE THE INCREASE IN SCHOOL AGED STUDENTS (3-18)
## BETWEEN 2019 AND 2036

pop_age <- pop_proj_data %>%                        # Get 2019+2036 Data 
  filter(county_fips=="000",                        # Filter for only Statewide Estimates
         age_in_yrs_num %>% between(3,18)) %>%      # Filter for only Ages 3-18 (School-Aged Population)
  group_by(year) %>%                                # Group By The Year    
  summarise(tot_pop_SA=sum(total))                  # Summarize The Total for Ages 3-18

Open Source Software Credits

censusapi by Hannah Recht: censusapi is an accessor for the United States Census Bureau’s APIs. More than 300 Census API endpoints are available, including Decennial Census, American Community Survey, Poverty Statistics, and Population Estimates APIs. This package is designed to let you get data from all of those APIs using the same main function—getCensus—and the same syntax for each dataset.

janitor by Sam Firke: janitor has simple functions for examining and cleaning dirty data. It was built with beginning and intermediate R users in mind and is optimized for user-friendliness. Advanced R users can already do everything covered here, but with janitor they can do it faster and save their thinking for the fun stuff.

rmarkdown by JJ Allaire, Yihui Xie, Jonathan McPherson, Javier Luraschi, Kevin Ushey, Aron Atkins, Hadley Wickham, Joe Cheng, Winston Chang, and Richard Iannone: The rmarkdown package helps you create dynamic analysis documents that combine code, rendered output (such as figures), and prose. You bring your data, code, and ideas, and R Markdown renders your content into a polished document that can be used to: do data science interactively within the RStudio IDE; Reproduce your analyses; Collaborate and share code with others; and communicate your results with others.

RStudio by RStudio - RStudio is an integrated development environment (IDE) for R. It includes a console, syntax-highlighting editor that supports direct code execution, as well as tools for plotting, history, debugging and workspace management.

sf by Edzer Pebesma: the sf package is a comprehensive resource for analyzing, manipulating, and visualizing spatial data files within R. It works seamlessly within the tidyverse syntax and, thus, is compatible with a number of different tidyverse-friendly tools.

tidycensus & tigris by Kyle Walker: tidycensus is an R package that allows users to interface with the US Census Bureau’s decennial Census and five-year American Community APIs and return tidyverse-ready data frames, optionally with simple feature geometry included. tigris is an R package that allows users to directly download and use TIGER/Line shapefiles from the US Census Bureau.

tidyverse by Hadley Wickham - The tidyverse is a set of packages that work in harmony because they share common data representations and API design. The tidyverse package is designed to make it easy to install and load core packages from the tidyverse in a single command. If you’d like to learn how to use the tidyverse effectively, the best place to start is R for data science.
